        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">For a description of Gower Street and its environs at the time, see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2664.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Freeman 1982</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">From the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-485.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Emma Wedgwood, [7 January 1839]</ref>, it is clear that the marriage of CD and Emma was originally to take place on 24 January, but the date was changed to 29 January.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Macaw Cottage—so called because of the gaudy colours of the walls and furniture (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2338.xml"><hi rend="italic">Emma Darwin</hi> (1915)</ref> 2: 18). The house was badly damaged by bombs during a World War II air raid. The site is now occupied by a part of the University of London.</note>
